.TH bluraybackup-ex 1 "March 2026" "bluraybackup-ex 2.1.0"
.SH NAME
bluraybackup-ex \- backup Blu-ray Disc Movies using libbluray
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B bluraybackup-ex
{-d \fIdevice\fR | -i \fIinput\fR} [-k \fIkeyfile\fR] [-m dir|iso] [-b \fIsize\fR] [-c] [\fIoutput\fR]

.B bluraybackup-ex
[\fIOPTION\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
\fBbluraybackup-ex\fP makes a decrypted copy of a Blu-ray Disc Movie
from a physical drive, an ISO/BIN disc image, or a directory
containing a BDMV structure.

Two output modes are available via \fB-m\fR:
.IP \fBdir\fP 8
Extract the full disc file tree into \fIoutput\fB/<disc-label>\fR/.
This is the default when \fB-m\fR is not supplied.
.IP \fBiso\fP 8
Produce a single decrypted ISO image at \fIoutput\fR.
Phase\~1 copies every sector of the source image verbatim;
Phase\~2 overwrites all encrypted .m2ts streams with AACS-decrypted
content obtained via libbluray.
Requires \fB-i\fR with a regular file (ISO/BIN image).
.PP
If \fIoutput\fR is omitted, only disc information is printed and the
program exits with status\~0.

To read protected Blu-ray media you need \fBlibaacs\fR installed and a
valid \fBKEYDB.cfg\fR file. Some discs also require \fBlibbdplus\fR.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\fB-d\fR, \fB--device\fR=\fIPATH\fR
Use a physical Blu-ray device path, such as \fB/dev/sr0\fR on Linux or
\fBD:\fR on Windows.
.TP
\fB-i\fR, \fB--input\fR=\fIPATH\fR
Use a local ISO/BIN image file or a directory containing a BDMV
structure.
.TP
\fB-k\fR, \fB--keydb\fR=\fIFILE\fR
Use the specified AACS keys database file.
If omitted, \fBbluraybackup-ex\fR searches the standard locations and
common filename variants (see
.B KEYDB SEARCH PATH
below).
.TP
\fB-m\fR, \fB--mode\fR=\fIMODE\fR
Output mode. Accepted values:
.RS
.IP \fBdir\fP 8
Extract the full disc file tree into \fIoutput\fB/<disc-label>\fR/
(default).
.IP \fBiso\fP 8
Write a single decrypted ISO image to \fIoutput\fR.
.RE
.TP
\fB-b\fR, \fB--buffer\fR=\fISIZE\fR
Set the I/O buffer size. Accepted suffixes: \fBk\fR/\fBK\fR (×1024),
\fBm\fR/\fBM\fR (×1024²), \fBg\fR/\fBG\fR (×1024³), or plain bytes.
Must be at least 6144 (one AACS unit, 3 BD sectors).
Default: \fB6144\fR. Larger values (e.g. \fB6m\fR) significantly
improve throughput on ISO images and SSDs.
.TP
\fB-c\fR, \fB--check\fR
Read every file on the disc to verify readability. On AACS-encrypted
discs each 6144-byte unit MAC is validated; errors are reported with
the file path and byte offset. Can be combined with \fIoutput\fR to
verify before extracting.
.TP
\fB-h\fR, \fB--help\fR
Print usage information.
.TP
\fB-v\fR, \fB--version\fR
Print version and license information.
.SH ARGUMENTS
.TP
\fIoutput\fR
Destination path. For \fBdir\fR mode, a directory that will be created
if necessary; the disc label is appended as a sub-directory. For
\fBiso\fR mode, the path of the output file. If omitted, the program
only prints disc information.
.SH BEHAVIOR
.TP
Input selection
\fB-d\fR and \fB-i\fR are mutually exclusive. If neither is provided,
the default device is used: \fB/dev/sr0\fR on Unix-like systems or
\fBD:\fR on Windows.
.TP
ISO mode requirement
\fB-m iso\fR requires the source (\fB-i\fR) to be a regular file.
Devices and BDMV directories are not supported in ISO mode.
.SH KEYDB SEARCH PATH
When \fB-k\fR is not provided, \fBbluraybackup-ex\fR searches:
.IP "Linux / macOS" 16
\fI~/.config/aacs/KEYDB.cfg\fR and filename variants
\fIkeydb.cfg\fR, \fIKeyDB.cfg\fR, \fIKEYDB.CFG\fR.
.IP Windows 16
\fI%APPDATA%\\\|aacs\\\|KEYDB.cfg\fR and the same variants.
Falls back to \fIKEYDB.cfg\fR in the current directory if the
environment variable is unset.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
\fB0\fP
Operation completed successfully.
.TP
\fB1\fP
An error occurred.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
Print disc information only
.B bluraybackup-ex -i /path/to/disc.iso
.TP
Extract file tree from a physical drive
.B bluraybackup-ex -d /dev/sr0 ~/backup
.TP
Extract file tree from an ISO image
.B bluraybackup-ex -i disc.iso ~/backup
.TP
Produce a decrypted ISO (6 MB buffer)
.B bluraybackup-ex -i encrypted.iso -m iso -b 6m decrypted.iso
.TP
Verify disc readability before extracting
.B bluraybackup-ex -i disc.iso -c ~/backup
.SH SEE ALSO
.P
\fBdvdbackup\fP(1)

